in\u003C/strong>, 64, sculptor, on the Vietnam Veterans Memorial (1982) in Washington, D.C.",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"It was a battle to keep the Vietnam Veterans Memorial simple and spare. I was moved by World War I memorials built by the French and British. They offered a much more realistic and sobering look at the high price of war, which is human life. When I went to the site [of what would become the monument] on Thanksgiving break [in 1980, when I was 20 and in my junior year at Yale], I felt a need to cut the earth and open it up. The structure isn’t so much an object inserted into the earth; it’s the earth itself being polished like a geode. I considered everything, even the walkway, which was put in to intentionally separate the wall from the ground. If you put the granite sidewalk all the way up against the wall, it would no longer be a polished geode — it’d be a curb. I put grass there. But no one could have predicted how popular it would be, so people trampled the grass and it died. "},{type:"text",value:"A year or two after the memorial was built, unbeknown to me, the architects of record worked with [the National] Park Service to put in [Belgian blocks on either side of the granite path]. That needs to be rethought because it’s an ugly detail. They’re out of scale. It drives me crazy every time I see it. — \u003Cem>L.G.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"diptych",value:{imageOne:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009392849",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009392849",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-origins-slide-H7ST.html",uri:"nyt://image/fa0d5bfc-a412-5c3f-a9b9-5054b90e275f",lastModified:"2024-04-15T18:19:40.219Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-15T18:19:40.219Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Chapman with the producer David Kershenbaum at a Los Angeles recording studio in 1987. The musician’s debut album will b