e writers] Charles Bukowski and Anaïs Nin because they told the truth about themselves, and it wasn’t always pretty. With my work, my goal was to be just as honest. “Pieces of You” wasn’t more developed than I was — I didn’t know how to play with a band, and I didn’t choose a producer who’d make me sound slicker or lend their experience to make me sound more polished. I wanted it to be a snapshot of who I was [between 16 and 19]: inexperienced, emotionally charged and trying to figure life out."},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009403711",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009403711",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/08/t-magazine/18tmag-origins-slide-0Q39.html",uri:"nyt://image/2ea01a09-7973-57f3-8007-2f6e3d7d3446",lastModified:"2024-04-15T18:52:38.802Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-15T18:52:38.802Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:""},altText:"An album cover, with the title \"pieces of you\" and text reading \"what we call human nature in actuality is human habit.\" The cover image is Jewel, smiling with hair blowing in her face in a wing-shaped cutout.",credit:"Courtesy of Craft Recordings and Jewel",summary:"",original:{width:1502,height:1506},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:1506,y1:0,x2:1502,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-origins-slide-0Q39/18tmag-origins-slide-0Q39-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:602},{width:1022,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-origins-slide-0Q39/18tmag-origins-slide-0Q39-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{width:1502,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-origins-slide-0Q39/18tmag-origins-slide-0Q39-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:1506}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:845,y1:0,x2:1502,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-ma