 close friends, [the former director of the U.S. Department of Labor Women’s Bureau] Karen Nussbaum, would tell me stories about organizing women office workers and what they had to go through. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>L.T.: \u003C/strong>I thought I had some lines that were hitting you over the head with the joke. Yet when the movie was released, those lines got the biggest response from the audience. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.F.: \u003C/strong>Both of us got a kick out of Dolly’s innocence. When she showed up the first day, she’d memorized the entire script. And then the day that Dolly sang — "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>L.T.: \u003C/strong>Oh, that was a glorious moment. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.F.: \u003C/strong>She used her long nails like a washboard and started to sing, “Working 9 to 5. …” Lily and I looked at each other and we knew: “This is it — we’ve got an anthem.” But I think my favorite shooting experiences were when we had the dead body in the back of the car. We went to the Apple Pan [a diner in Los Angeles] because Dolly wanted to get a cheeseburger, remember? "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>L.T.: \u003C/strong>Everybody would tell stories about their life, and we just fell in love with each other."},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.F.: \u003C/strong>Our worlds are so different. Our backgrounds are so different. Our senses of comedy — I mean, I don’t really have one. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>L.T.: \u003C/strong>Jane was so earnest. She felt so passionate about every activist problem that she was trying to solve. It was inspiring and endearing. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.F.: \u003C/strong>Since then, we’ve done seven seasons of [the Netflix TV series] “Grace and Frankie” [which ran from 2015 to 2022]. Ten days after we wrapped, we started a movie that we both like a lot called “Moving On.” When that came out [in 2023], I was interested in the reviews — almost every one of them talked about our chemistry. And it was like, “Well, maybe we should always work together.” — \u003Cem>E.R.A.\u003C/em>"},{type:"text",value:"Fonda: Hair: Jonathan Hanousek at Exclusive Artists Management. Makeup: David Deleon at Allyson Spiegelman Management. Tomlin: Hair: Darrell Redleaf Fielder at Aim Artists Agency. Makeup: Shelley Rucker at Aim Artists Agency. On-set producer: Joy Thomas. Photo assistant: Jeremy Eric Sinclair. Digital tech: Aron Norman",className:"g-detailblock"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"sectionheader",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>MARC JACOBS, FASHION DESIGNER, AND CINDY SHERMAN, ARTIST\u003C/strong> Have collaborated on multiple projects for the Marc Jacobs brand, from a 2005 photo book to the spring 2024 campaign.",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009392799",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009392799",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-Z7UH.html",uri:"nyt://image/060a7937-4905-5b6c-8466-bdea847689e0",lastModified:"2024-04-17T17:45:23.121Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T17:45:23.121Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"From left: Jacobs, 61, and Sherman, 70, photographed at Go Studios in Hell’s Kitchen, Manhattan, on March 5, 2024."},altText:"Marc Jacobs and Cindy Sherman both stand in front of a gray background wearing black shirts and raising their right arms.",credit:"Bon Duke",summary:"",original:{width:9443,height:12111},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:12111,y1:2262,x2:9443,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-Z7UH/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-Z7UH-articleLarge-v2.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:626},{width:982,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-Z7UH/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-Z7UH-jumbo-v2.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{wid