cellent, it’s [expletive] excellent.” He says that when he’s really excited. You created some hilarious characters. There was one where you were both older, sitting on a bench. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>C.S.: \u003C/strong>Rifling through a big bag. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.J.: \u003C/strong>That image became a billboard on Melrose [Avenue in Los Angeles]. It was great because fashion campaigns like that didn’t exist back then. Nobody would’ve ever said, “\u003Cem>That’s \u003C/em>our ad,” because it wasn’t exactly selling clothes or bags. But it was exciting. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>C.S.: \u003C/strong>What’s funny is that you’d asked me, a year or two ago during Covid, to do something — I don’t even remember what it was. I’d gained a bit of weight, so I was self-conscious and kept turning you down. [For the 2024 campaign I ended up doing] some of the outfits were a little tight. The people assisting me said, “We can fix that.” And I said, “No, no, it’s [perfect for] the character.” I guess I could’ve thought of someone who was trying to hide, but I decided, “No, she seems like she could just let it all hang out in her leather pants.” How do you feel when you see different types of women wearing your pieces or putting them together in unusual ways? "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.J.: \u003C/strong>It’s the ultimate validation. Of all the stuff that exists out there, they’re spending their money on something I’ve made. How about you with collectors? "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>C.S.: \u003C/strong>Sometimes it’s a little weird. I remember an early series of horizontal pictures that I called “The Centerfolds” (1981) — I thought they were kind of disturbing, but some collector said, “I have that one hanging over my bed because it’s so sexy.” And I’m thinking, “Ugh, I don’t want to know that.” But you can’t control what happens to a piece. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.J.: \u003C/strong>Or what other people see in it. Feedback is part of the equation. It’s like, “I’m not just doing this for me. I need you.” — \u003Cem>E.R.A.\u003C/em>"},{type:"text",value:"Production: Prodn. Hair: Tsuki at Streeters. Makeup assistant: Nanase. Photo assistants: John Temones, Tony Jarum, Logan Khidekel",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"ad",value:{id:50,size:void 0}}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"sectionheader",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>CARLOS NAZARIO, STYLIST, AND WILLY CHAVARRIA, FASHION DESIGNER\u003C/strong> Have worked together on three collections since 2022.",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009392797",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009392797",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-1CB0.html",uri:"nyt://image/c8bb3da2-e9c0-5fb1-9db9-b078550fe8d5",lastModified:"2024-04-17T17:44:30.679Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T17:44:30.679Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"From left: Nazario, 36, and Chavarria, 56, photographed at Chavarria’s studio in Greenpoint, Brooklyn, on March 18, 2024."},altText:"Willy Chavarria, wearing a black T-shirt and necklaces, stands and crosses his arms. Next to him sits Carlos Nazario, wearing a white T-shirt.",credit:"Emiliano Granado",summary:"",original:{width:3000,height:2400},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:2400,y1:0,x2:3000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-1CB0/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-1CB0-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:480},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-1CB0/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-1CB0-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:819},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-1CB0/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-1CB0-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:1638}]},{name: