ltimore police. Mink played an escaped mental patient; she did a nude tap dance."},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.S.: \u003C/strong>I’d get upset when the press would call us unprofessional because, although it was true that not one of us had ever taken an acting lesson, we were incredibly professional. And none of it was ad-libbed. John wouldn’t have tolerated that. He knew every comma, every “and,” every “but.”"},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.W.: \u003C/strong>What’s that French term for people who go crazy when they’re together? "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.S.: \u003C/strong>“Folie à something”? "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.W.: \u003C/strong>“Folie à famille.” Everybody chipped in, and we just went for it. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>T: \u003C/strong>Mink, were there any scenes you refused to shoot?"},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.S.: \u003C/strong>Before we started filming “Pink Flamingos” [1972, in which Stole plays the proprietor of a black-market baby ring], John very casually said, “Will you set your hair on fire?” And I said, “Yes, that’ll look great on film.” But then as the moment approached, I panicked."},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.W.: \u003C/strong>I was on pot when I thought of that. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.S.: \u003C/strong>It would’ve been great, except that I’d be bald today. I think that’s the only thing I ever refused to do. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>T: \u003C/strong>What’ve you learned from each other? "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.S.: \u003C/strong>In the early films, we all acted largely. We spoke in italics. In the later ones, when I’d start to behave that way, John would say, “Take it down.” I was shocked [the first time he said it]. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.W.: \u003C/strong>When we made those early movies, I was influenced by the theater of the ridiculous — by cruelty, shouting and craziness. It wasn’t them overacting, it was me telling them to overact. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.S.: \u003C/strong>I have enormous respect for John, and John for me. Aside from the fact that I love him dearly, I don’t know where I’d be if I hadn’t met him. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.W.: \u003C/strong>And we’ve never had the same boyfriend. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.S.: \u003C/strong>Or wanted the same boyfriend. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>J.W.: \u003C/strong>Mink and I have been through a lot together. We’ve fought, we’ve made up. I don’t trust people who don’t have old friends. For me, they outlast family. Mink and I are even going to be buried together in the same graveyard. We call it Disgraceland. — \u003Cem>N.H.\u003C/em>"},{type:"text",value:"Waters: Makeup: Cheryl Pickles Kinion. Photo assistants: Daniel Garton, Ashley Poole",className:"g-detailblock"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"sectionheader",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>COBY KENNEDY AND HANK WILLIS THOMAS, ARTISTS\u003C/strong> Have spent three decades collaborating on public art installations and community-focused projects, including 2023’s “Reach,” a more than 2,700-pound fiberglass-and-resin sculpture at Chicago’s O’Hare International Airport of two hands nearly touching.",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009395114",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009395114",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-thesetwo-slide-A2BZ.html",uri:"nyt://image/bc7b4dd5-2c89-5c2d-a756-0b26fd30a16f",lastModified:"2024-04-17T18:07:44.218Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T18:07:44.218Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"From left: Kennedy, 47, and Thomas, 48, photographed at Thomas’s studio in East Williamsburg, Brooklyn, on Feb. 28, 2024."},altText:"Coby Kennedy and Hank Willis Thomas pose in front of a gray background.",credit:"D’Angelo Lovell Williams",summary:"",original:{width:5