We’d been in a group show together before and had mutual friends, and I was excited about the work I was seeing Michael make. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>MICHAEL BAILEY-GATES: \u003C/strong>It was me, Bobbi and maybe two or three other people. I had this party trick of being able to talk really fast, like an auctioneer. When I said certain phrases, one of them would stand up, and another would scream at the top of their lungs or throw an object at someone."},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>B.S.M.: \u003C/strong>It felt like the beginning of us making things together on the fly. We both had this down-to-get-into-it energy that was well matched. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.B.G.: \u003C/strong>We shared an urgency to make work come to life. Sometimes it’s as simple as being a body for another person. I’ve been the lead in Bobbi’s performances, and I’ve been in the background, lying on a floor covered in red paint. Performance art in New York at the time was about executing an idea without a lot of money. These days, I don’t go into a shoot thinking we’re performing, but it’s very much that: The camera is the audience looking back at us. "},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>B.S.M.: \u003C/strong>Michael has this ability to see the kaleidoscopic possibility of someone’s self- expression. Around 2018, I was out as nonbinary to my close friends and finding my new name. I took a break from auditions and started working part-time as a substitute teacher. When a film I’d shot the year before got into [the 2019] Sundance [Film Festival], it was an invitation to step back into the spotlight. I’d shaved my head and was nervous about that formal, public coming- out moment. It just felt so cringe. I went to Los Angeles before going to Sundance and made some pictures with Michael that were only for us. Those were the first images of Bobbi that entered the world."},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>M.B.G.: \u003C/strong>I never want to make a picture of somebody that’s not reflective of them. I’ve chosen in my practice to always focus on a small group of friends, and those collaborations are the grounding force of my work. Without them, what would my pictures be? They’d be something less precious. — \u003Cem>C.R.\u003C/em>"},{type:"text",value:"Makeup: Zenia Jaeger at Streeters using Submission Beauty. Hair assistant: Drew Martin. Production: Resin Projects. Photo assistants: Michael Preman, Jack Buster",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"text",value:"These interviews have been edited and condensed.",className:"g-detailblock"}]}]}},{type:"article",value:{asset:"100000009382381",slug:"18tmag-beginagain",sourceId:"100000009382381",bylines:[{renderedRepresentation:"Interviews by Michael Snyder, M.H. Miller and Emily Lordi",prefix:"By",creators:[{displayName:"Michael Snyder"},{displayName:"M.H. Miller"},{displayName:"Emily Lordi"}]}],headline:{default:"Begin Again",seo:""},summary:"What it’s like to make new art after many years or amid new challenges — or to change careers completely.",credits:void 0,headerImage:{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopVideo",assetSlug:"100000009403287",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Video",sourceId:"100000009403287",url:"https://www.nytimes.com/video/embedded/t-magazine/100000009403287/jordi-roca-loop.html",uri:"nyt://video/c939c048-aae4-519b-bcfc-08bc2be3f2e8",lastModified:"2024-04-18T12:25:38.244Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-18T12:25:38.244Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[{renderedRepresentation:"By Anna Bosch Miralpeix",prefix:"By",creators:[{displayName:"Anna Bosch Miralpeix",givenName:"",familyName:"",url:"https://www.nytimes.com/by/anna-bosch-miralpeix",uri:"nyt://person/4cef8a0a-aace-5bcb-acf9-12ee956ea1fa",bioUrl:"https://www.nytimes.com/by/anna-bosch-miralpeix",honorificSuffix:"",honorificPrefix:"",description:"",promotionalMedia:null}]}],summary:"Jordi Roca.",renditions:[{width:192,height:240,url:"https://vp.nyt.com/video/2024/04/08/117215_1_jordi-roca-loop_wg_