eling manual labor as a child.] The power of painting’s often the absences: what’s not there, what’s implicit. You don’t know what happened before and you don’t know what will happen after. In film, you have an opportunity for elaboration."},{type:"text",value:"I’ve tried hard not to read reviews of the film, though a friend sent me one. It was positive but what [the critic] wrote at the end, I’ll never forget. He said, “But I can’t say this film is entertaining.” [\u003Cem>Laughs.\u003C/em>] With film, some of us expect entertainment, to have a great time. And that response does frame the way we distinguish film from painting. As a painter, I don’t stand in front of [Pablo Picasso’s] “Guernica” and go, “This isn’t entertaining!” I didn’t approach filmmaking as anything different from painting. I wanted the film to be a painting in motion. The way I make decisions in the studio, about how to follow my intuition or instincts, or how to lay out a composition, was the same process I used on set. The difference is I had an extraordinary cinematographer and cast of actors to help me realize the paintings in my head."},{type:"text",value:"At its essence, “Exhibiting Forgiveness” is about generational healing. I took on this project because I wanted to have a conversation with my children about the world I grew up in, which is so different from the world they’ve grown up in. And I think making the film helped resolve something within me. The revelation I had is that I can’t make my father out as the villain in my mind. He’s a victim of violence himself. And even though [he] created challenges for me, I’ve never wondered whether or not he loved me. — \u003Cem>M.H.M.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>Bárbara Sánchez-Kane,\u003C/strong> artist",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009395128",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009395128",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ.html",uri:"nyt://image/375b337c-e485-50ec-a777-690d6c2b2d63",lastModified:"2024-04-17T15:39:00.329Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T15:39:00.329Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Sánchez-Kane, 36, photographed at his studio (the artist uses she/her and he/him pronouns interchangeably) in Mexico City on Jan. 22, 2024."},altText:"Bárbara Sánchez-Kane wearing a double-breasted black jacket stands in a doorway.",credit:"Ana Topoleanu. Artwork, clockwise from left: Bárbara Sánchez-Kane, “La Diegada,” 2016, courtesy of the artist and Estudio Sánchez-Kane; Bárbara Sánchez-Kane, “Tragic Stages,” 2023, courtesy of the artist and Estudio Sánchez-Kane; Bárbara Sánchez-Kane, “Moctezuma’s Revenge,” 2017, performance by Sierva M, courtesy of the artist and Estudio Sánchez-Kane, photo: Karla Ximena",summary:"",original:{width:2000,height:3000},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:3000,y1:0,x2:2000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:900},{width:683,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{width:1366,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:2048}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:1125,y1:0,x2:2000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ/18tmag-beginagain-slide-X4EQ-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:1047,y1:0,x2:2000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-beginagai