 doesn’t matter what you’ve studied or haven’t. When I feel like the worst sculptor, I think, “Well, at least I’m a good designer.” And when I feel like a great sculptor, I might look at [the clothes in my studio] and think, “Those terrible [expletive] trousers!” Expanding into other fields is a way to embrace yourself. All we have is our imagination, which allows us to create things: objects, garments, skins that we wear when we go out into the world. I’m not saying they’ll save us, but maybe they can help us navigate the transition to another universe. — \u003Cem>M.S.\u003C/em> "},{type:"text",value:"These interviews have been edited and condensed.",className:"g-detailblock"}]}]}},{type:"article",value:{asset:"100000009382501",slug:"18tmag-theend",sourceId:"100000009382501",bylines:[{renderedRepresentation:"By John Wogan and M.H. Miller",prefix:"By",creators:[{displayName:"John Wogan"},{displayName:"M.H. Miller"}]}],headline:{default:"When the Beginning Is Also the End",seo:""},summary:"People who found great creative success in one field — before life took them in a totally different direction.",credits:void 0,headerImage:{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009399454",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009399454",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/05/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-TR40-copy.html",uri:"nyt://image/29c8d7d2-764c-5729-8276-daea315206aa",lastModified:"2024-04-05T16:42:36.263Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-05T16:42:36.263Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Miguel Adrover."},altText:"",credit:"Catarina Osório de Castro",summary:"",original:{width:6895,height:6895},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:6895,y1:0,x2:6895,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-TR40-copy/18tmag-theend-slide-TR40-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:600},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.ny