present one runway show, which I called Out of My Mind. It was made up of personal garments I’d repurposed. I was 46. "},{type:"text",value:"I’d been trying to find a way out of this unsustainable industry, this imaginary fantasy that fashion creates. My collections dealt with social justice, environmental consciousness and diversity before those topics became mainstream, and some seasons I didn’t sell anything. I never had a sugar daddy, and I invested everything I made back into the company. "},{type:"text",value:"I miss New York a lot. I’m homesick for it, but it isn’t the same city, and fashion is very different, too — it feels inauthentic and disconnected from reality. When I was doing consulting and research for Alexander McQueen [in the mid-90s], we had no money. But the energy was amazing. When you don’t have money, that’s when you’re most creative. Now all of these big companies have so much money that it feels like a different world. [Still] I’d love to have the chance to put on one last presentation, one last show to express how I feel today and how I see the world right now. "},{type:"text",value:"When I left New York, I decided to come to Majorca, where my parents have a farm. I started doing photography accidentally; I had no knowledge of cameras, every day was a process of me learning something totally on my own. There was a 300-year-old well on the property with no water inside, and I realized it could be my studio. It’s kind of like a basement; light comes from a little window high above. It reminds me of my apartment in New York. It’s where I develop my [projects]. I use things that surround me: tulips and rose bushes, fruit trees, a tropical garden, chickens. "},{type:"text",value:"When I got here, I didn’t have a team [as I did in fashion], and one of the challenges was being surrounded by people who don’t care about what I did or what I’m doing. Photography was the ideal thing to do because I don’t need anybody, I can do it on my own. I don’t have any models; I started working with mannequins and, for many years, I collected them on eBay or from secondhand stores on the island. [I decided] I’d rather not use models — when you photograph human beings, they’re pretending or acting, and I was running away from that."},{type:"text",value:"It’s been nine years since I found photography, and I’m really happy. I have a monograph coming out later this year. The photographs are like my biography. I’ve developed my style in photography and I have a creative language. Fashion was the platform I once used, but the soul inside me is the same. — \u003Cem>interview by J.W.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>Ralph Ellison,\u003C/strong> writer, circa 1913-94",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009391850",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009391850",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD.html",uri:"nyt://image/278880d9-5924-5f33-bc9b-0e3eaa41477e",lastModified:"2024-04-17T19:28:25.791Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T19:28:25.791Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Ralph Ellison, the author of the 1952 novel “Invisible Man,” in June 1957 during his fellowship at the American Academy in Rome."},altText:"Ralph Ellison sits in front of an a typewriter under an awning writing.",credit:"James Whitmore/The Life Picture Collection/Shutterstock",summary:"",original:{width:3558,height:3589},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:3589,y1:0,x2:3558,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:605},{width:1016,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{width:2031,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:2048}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:2001,y1:0,x2:3558,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:1862,y1:0,x2:3558,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:549}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:3589,y1:0,x2:3558,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD/18tmag-theend-slide-WAJD-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:1816}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"Ralph Ellison spent seven years writing his only completed novel, “Invisible Man,” and its publication in 1952, when he was in his late 30s, not only catapulted him to literary fame but made him nothing less than a spokesperson for postwar America. His contemporary Norman Mailer would write of him that at his best, “He writes so perfectly that one can never forget the experience of reading him.” “Invisible Man,” a surreal picaresque that follows an unnamed Black protagonist — “a man of substance, of flesh and bone,” Ellison writes — as he travels through a country full of people who “refuse to see me,” is a book of such remarkable confidence that Ellison’s career, in later years, became mired in questions of what next? Ellison, a prolific writer of essays, reviews and criticism, worked for years on a follow-up, suffering one setback when a 1967 house fire destroyed portions of his manuscript. When he died in 1994, he left behind thousands of pages of drafts, fragments and unfinished tangents. Ellison’s literary executor and longtime friend, John F. Callahan, tried to edit the material down into a “single, coherent narrative,” as he put it, and published the result, called “Juneteenth,” in 1999; the New York Times critic Michiko Kakutani called it “disappointingly provisional and incomplete.” Ellison often struggled with writing. He once likened his second novel to a “bad case of constipation” and, in a 1958 letter to his friend the author Saul Bellow, Ellison wrote, “I’ve got a natural writer’s block as big as the Ritz and as stubborn as a grease spot on a gabardine suit.” — \u003Cem>M.H.M.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>Charles Laughton,\u003C/strong> actor and director, 1899-1962",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009391849",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009391849",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF.html",uri:"nyt://image/0d805c1f-4e6c-5099-98ad-6bca2d765594",lastModified:"2024-04-17T15:55:31.436Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T15:55:31.436Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"The actor turned director Charles Laughton with the actress Sally Jane Bruce on the set of “The Night of the Hunter” (1955)."},altText:"Charles Laughton sits in a director's chair wearing a straw hat with a girl looking through a viewfinder in his lap.",credit:"Everett Collection",summary:"",original:{width:2051,height:1533},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:1533,y1:0,x2:2051,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:448},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:765},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:1531}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:1343,y1:190,x2:2051,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:1303,y1:230,x2:2051,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:549}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:1533,y1:0,x2:2051,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF/18tmag-theend-slide-YELF-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:1345}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"Born in the last year of the 19th century, Charles Laughton left his family’s successful hotel business at the age of 26 to study acting at the Royal Academy of Arts in London. What he lacked in movie star looks — the critic J. Hoberman described him as “coarse-featured, overweight and slovenly” — he made up for in talent. Following a successful stage career in London’s West End, he turned to film, making a name for himself as a versatile character actor in the 1930s and ’40s. In 1955, at the age of 55, he made his most indelible contribution to his craft, directing “The Night of the Hunter,” a film noir so dark it easily passes today as horror. (William Friedkin, the director of 1973’s “The Exorcist,” described it as “one of the scariest films ever made.”) Robert Mitchum plays a terrifying ex-convict posing as a preacher and stalking the children of his former cellmate in order to find a hidden fortune. While casting Lillian Gish in the role of the children’s caretaker, Laughton told the actress about his disappointment in audiences’ lack of attention for movies, how they “slump down with their heads back, or eat candy and popcorn. I want them to sit up straight again,” he said. Though now often ranked among the greatest American movies, “The Night of the Hunter” — released just a few years before Alfred Hitchcock’s “Psycho” (1960) made the psychological thriller into a marketable genre — was a commercial flop. Reviews were mixed; The New York Times’s Bosley Crowther called it “a weird and intriguing endeavor.” Years later, Terry Sanders, a second-unit director of the film, wrote that “the rejection by critics and the indifference of audiences hit [Laughton] hard and crushed his spirit. It wasn’t just disappointment he felt, it was utter and deeply debilitating devastation.” He never directed a second movie. — \u003Cem>M.H.M.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>Willis Alan Ramsey,\u003C/strong> 73, Loveland, Colo.",className:"g-heading3block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009391851",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009391851",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX.html",uri:"nyt://image/c9d5301f-8726-5c64-b32e-0648a61ead1a",lastModified:"2024-04-17T19:29:02.200Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T19:29:02.200Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"The singer-songwriter Willis Alan Ramsey, photographed at Sam’s Town Point bar in Austin, Texas, on March 14, 2024."},altText:"Willis Alan Ramsey stands with his hands behind his back wearing a cowboy hat.",credit:"Caleb Santiago Alvarado",summary:"",original:{width:2250,height:3000},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:3000,y1:0,x2:2250,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:800},{width:768,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{width:1536,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:2048}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:1266,y1:0,x2:2250,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:1178,y1:0,x2:2250,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:550}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:3000,y1:0,x2:2250,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX/18tmag-theend-slide-Q5FX-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:2400}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"The singer-songwriter Willis Alan Ramsey, originally from Alabama, released his self-titled debut album in 1972, becoming a forebear of the alt-country genre. Jimmy Buffett and Lyle Lovett became devoted fans. More than 50 years later, Ramsey still hasn’t completed his second album. ",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"text",value:"I started trying to write songs around 1968. My first song was just awful, but I got better over time. I dropped out of college twice, the second time in 1970, from the University of Texas [at Austin], after discovering a folk club where I became an opening act for $5 a night. Those were golden, halcyon days in Austin filled with sunshine and margaritas and very little traffic. That fall, I left to begin performing at colleges around the country. I was briefly back in Austin to play at U.T. and, somehow, during two days there, I’d managed to play for Gregg Allman and Leon Russell, two of the most influential musicians of that decade. They both gave me their cards and said to look them up if I ever made it their way. [I went to Los Angeles] and recorded a demo at Skyhill, Leon’s personal home studio, and he basically offered me the moon to sign with his new label, Shelter Records [which folded in 1981]. I’d just turned 20. Over the next year, I recorded my first and only album to ever be released [“Willis Alan Ramsey,” often known as the Green Album for its green cover]."},{type:"text",value:"I finished the record when I was 21. I was just a kid. Leon gave me my career, to the extent that I’ve had one [but the reason I never released another record was also] Leon’s fault. He told me that if I signed with Shelter, he’d show me the studio and how it worked, and he did. I immediately wanted to learn everything I could about the recording process. I used seven studios and three rhythm sections [to make the record]. I was given carte blanche. The budget was 85 grand. I could do it for 200 grand [now], but I can’t do it any cheaper. I’d need to rehearse every musician. And my songs are all over the place. I get bored doing one particular style."},{type:"text",value:"I’m the most frustrated recording artist you’ve probably ever met in your life. But I still feel I’ll figure something out. I’ve always been optimistic. I’ve got at least three more records of material. I’m pretty tough on myself in terms of writing, and I’m very attached to what I’ve written. I just haven’t been able to get a deal that’d work for me. I mean, the world works, you know? I think the key is just to work with the world. — \u003Cem>interview by M.H.M.\u003C/em>"},{type:"text",value:"Photo assistant: Sergio Flores",className:"g-detailblock"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"\u003Cstrong>Harper Lee,\u003C/strong> write