h me, and people would gather around me while I was drawing, sometimes 20 to 30 of them. The kids were happy to have a drawing, but it didn’t really change the bullying pattern."},{type:"text",value:"I saved most of my [childhood] drawings and gave them to my nephew. Unluckily, he lost them. This is virtually the only one that survived, and I gave it to my wife as a present. "},{type:"text",value:"It’s quite interesting to see the size of things — the difference between the houses and the people — and most of all, the idea of space that was already in the drawing. [If I were to redraw this today] it’d be a bit more meticulous, more worked out. But it’s an indication of things that would come later. My skepticism is embedded in this drawing without my doing that consciously — this quite specific, sardonic sense of humor. When I found it again, I had to laugh very, very hard. — \u003Cem>J.H.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Do Ho Suh, 62, visual artist",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009405294",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009405294",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/09/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ.html",uri:"nyt://image/c8c409d8-2ebb-5448-b601-1e461087fe0a",lastModified:"2024-04-17T20:43:17.641Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T20:43:17.641Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Do Ho Suh, “Tiger Mask” (1971)."},altText:"",credit:"Courtesy of the artist © Do Ho Suh",summary:"",original:{width:3014,height:2613},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:2613,y1:0,x2:3014,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:520},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:888},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:1776}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:2154,y1:459,x2:3014,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:2095,y1:518,x2:3014,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:549}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:2613,y1:0,x2:3014,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-L6NJ-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:1561}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"This drawing is based on a Japanese anime character, Tiger Mask, that was really popular in the ’70s. Back in those days, Korean TV broadcast Japanese anime in black and white. Everybody at school watched. The character is a pro wrestler who puts on a tiger mask to disguise his identity. I drew the mask directly from the anime. I was probably 9. "},{type:"text",value:"Once my friends saw it, they all wanted one. Demand for tiger masks became much greater than supply. Some of the rich kids wanted to trade their Japanese pencils — which had graphics or custom characters on the surface — and colorful erasers for a drawing. My parents couldn’t afford those things, and they weren’t available in Korea. The kids’ parents must have traveled to Japan, which was quite rare back then, and brought them back. [Eventually] I had a box full of those pencils, but I didn’t have the guts to actually use them. The pencils are untouched; the erasers are dried out. For some reason, my mom kept them all these years. — \u003Cem>J.H.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Niki Nakayama, 49, chef and Restaurant owner",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:""},{type:"text",value:"Tonkatsu is a Japanese home-style staple. It’s a breaded, deep-fried pork cutlet — “ton” means “pork” and “katsu” is a sort of translation of “cutlet” — and it was my absolute favorite food when I was a kid. When my mom made tonkatsu, she’d have my sister and me do the breading, and we really bonded over that. It helped me understand family. We’d set up in the dining room and dredge the cutlets in flour, dip them into the egg wash, cover them with dried breadcrumbs and stack them high on paper plates that we’d bring in to my mother to fry up. Our kitchen had high countertops, and I can remember her standing at the stove in these three-inch platform clogs she’d wear to be a little taller. "},{type:"text",value:"I loved seeing how something became something else — it felt like unraveling magic. One day when I was about 9, I came home from school and got the brilliant idea to make my own [but with chicken]. I grabbed some drumsticks from the freezer, did the breading and, while standing on a stool, dipped them in hot oil. (I never admitted this to my mom.) When they turned the color they were supposed to, I was so proud. I bit into one and it was still frozen. That was my first shock of “I can’t believe I didn’t make [this thing] the way I imagined it would be.”"},{type:"text",value:"Anytime I was in Japan, especially in my 20s, my friends there would ask what subarashii gochiso, or “the best thing one could possibly eat,” was for me. I’d say tonkatsu, and they’d be like, “What?!,” because it’s such a simple dish — it was like asking for a sandwich. It isn’t the sort of thing I specialize in at my restaurant [N/Naka in Los Angeles], and I don’t have it often anymore because, as I age, I’m trying to eat lighter, but I still associate it with deliciousness and with happiness. Ever since childhood, I’ve thought of food as being about coming together and cooking as an expression of care and love. Having been on the receiving end of that, I do the work that I do to try to make people happy. — \u003Cem>K.G.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Marina Abramović, 77, performance artist",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009391839",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009391839",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ.html",uri:"nyt://image/782c972e-e8c8-5692-84db-16f6300dcab9",lastModified:"2024-04-17T20:42:15.334Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T20:42:15.334Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Marina Abramović, “Truck Accident (I)” (1963)."},altText:"A painting of two vehicles crashing into each other.",credit:"© Marina Abramović/Courtesy of the Marina Abramović Archives/ARS, 2024",summary:"",original:{width:4541,height:4010},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:4010,y1:0,x2:4541,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:530},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:904},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:1809}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:3282,y1:728,x2:4541,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:3193,y1:817,x2:4541,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:549}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:4010,y1:0,x2:4541,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-QOKQ-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:1590}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"When I was a teenager in Communist Yugoslavia, there were these ugly green trucks that weighed so much, they often fell over. I started taking photographs of them and trying to paint them at home. But that wasn’t enough for me, so I bought some toy cars and left them on the highway to see if the real trucks would smash them; they were always untouched. I was fascinated by car crashes. Then when I was 17 or 18 years old, I painted the big car smashed and the little car protected — the idea that innocence survives everything. "},{type:"text",value:"My mother studied art history, and I was always going to museums. When I was a baby, my first words weren’t “mama” or “papa”; they were “El Greco.” I had my first exhibition at a youth center when I was 14. They mostly had group shows, but I made so much work that I had my own show. I always say I was jealous of Mozart because he started at 5. "},{type:"text",value:"I didn’t know then that painting wasn’t my ultimate goal. It takes a long time to realize who you are. I remember the incredible joy of going into my studio — an extra space in my family’s apartment — with my little cup of Turkish coffee. I would be so much in the dream of painting that I’d accidentally drink turpentine instead of the coffee. "},{type:"text",value:"Though I wasn’t aware of it [until recently], this crash represents the energy that I’d create in my early performances: two bodies running toward each other, crashing into each other and making this blurry image. My research today is about the body and how to create a field in which you aren’t afraid of pain, of dying, of limits. When you’re young, you don’t see the straight line but, [looking back] it all seems so logical. — \u003Cem>J.H.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Deborah Roberts, 61, visual artist",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009391836",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009391836",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH.html",uri:"nyt://image/be4940af-9a6b-59f3-a65f-94297e671417",lastModified:"2024-04-17T20:40:47.561Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T20:40:47.561Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Deborah Roberts, “James” (1982)."},altText:"A drawing of a boy resting his chin on his knee.",credit:"Courtesy of the artist",summary:"",original:{width:2978,height:2980},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:2980,y1:0,x2:2978,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:600},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{width:2047,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:2048}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:1675,y1:0,x2:2978,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-K1FH-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"vid