ources coming from two different areas. But if you look at my collages today, my whole idea’s about seeing people as humans, as children, as vulnerable. I think this is a very vulnerable piece. — \u003Cem>J.H.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"David Henry Hwang, 66, playwright",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009405297",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009405297",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/09/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU.html",uri:"nyt://image/33e325a0-bc3d-5623-88f1-29618e02f47b",lastModified:"2024-04-17T20:43:07.716Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T20:43:07.716Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"David Henry Hwang, manuscript of “Only Three Generations” (1968)."},altText:"The opening page of a manuscript.",credit:"Courtesy of David Henry Hwang. Photo: Lance Brewer",summary:"",original:{width:7915,height:5654},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:5430,y1:288,x2:7679,x1:198},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU-articleLarge-v2.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:412},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU-jumbo-v2.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:704},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU-superJumbo-v2.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:1408}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:4965,y1:755,x2:7679,x1:198},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU-videoSixteenByNine600-v2.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:4819,y1:901,x2:7679,x1:198},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU-facebookJumbo-v2.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:550}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:5430,y1:288,x2:7679,x1:198},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU/18tmag-juvenilia-slide-9DUU-mobileMasterAt3x-v2.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:1237}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"I was about 10 years old, and my maternal grandmother got sick and it looked like she might be close to the end. I remember feeling that that’d be quite tragic — not only would I lose my grandmother but she also happened to be the family historian. I was one of those kids who, for whatever reason, was always really interested in hearing about family history. "},{type:"text",value:"I was born and raised in Los Angeles, but my mom grew up in the Philippines, where my maternal grandparents still lived, so I asked my parents if I could spend a summer there. I went and collected what we’d now call oral histories from my grandmother on cassette tapes, then came back and compiled them into a 60-page family history, “Only Three Generations,” which was [photocopied] and distributed to my family members. Then in the early aughts, someone — my uncle, I think — went and printed two or three dozen copies as a bound version."},{type:"text",value:"I wasn’t someone who felt [that] writing was my calling. I didn’t do another major writing project until I got to college and started writing plays, so I find it interesting that the one time I took on [something] like this was to contextualize myself in a historical framework. That’s consistent with what I’ve done as an adult: sometimes being at sea about who I am and looking at history to gain a sense of self."},{type:"text",value:"The [history] starts with my great-great-grandfather, then the second [part]’s about my great-grandfather and then the third section’s about my grandmother’s generation. I [used] their real names. I think I was trying to be fairly accurate, as opposed to when it later became the basis of my [1996] play “Golden Child.” There’s a lot more liberty taken there. When we did the play on Broadway, my grandmother was still alive and came to see the show. She was supportive of it, but I feel like she liked this version better. — \u003Cem>J.A.R.\u003C/em> "},{type:"text",value:"These interviews have been edited and condensed. ",className:"g-detailblock"}]}]}},{type:"article",value:{asset:"100000009382408",slug:"18tmag-beginners",sourceId:"100000009382408",bylines:[{renderedRepresentation:"Interviews by Juan A. Ramírez and Emily Lordi",prefix:"By",creators:[{displayName:"Juan A. Ramírez"},{displayName:"Emily Lordi"}]}],headline:{default:"Beginners",seo:""},summary:"A first album, a first restaurant, a first time on Broadway: Ten debuts happening right now.",credits:void 0,headerImage:{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009403729",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009403729",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/08/t-magazine/18tmag-beginners-slide-5B8L-copy.html",uri:"nyt://image/b4577ae9-269b-574a-a815-ab9e6623ddf5",lastModified:"2024-04-12T19:26:39.016Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-12T19:26:39.016Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Ice Spice."},altText:"",credit:"Shikeith",summary:"",original:{width:4096,height:2732},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:2732,y1:0,x2:4096,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-beginners-slide-5B8L-copy/18tmag-beginners-slide-5B8L-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:400},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-beginners-slide-5B8L-copy/18tmag-beginners-slide-5B8L-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:683},{width:2048,url:"https