s but not feel like I’m shaping the play to respond to these fluctuations.”"},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>How she found her way to playwriting:\u003C/strong> “I was in the Public’s Emerging Writers Group in 2018, which was my introduction to theater. I was never a theater kid; film was my first love — I’d done my thesis in screenwriting. After I graduated [from New York University], I’d written a play, and I used that to get into the [playwriting] group. The idea for ‘Jordans’ came partly from my own experience post-grad of being fired three times in a row and being like, ‘What’s going on?’ I was also trying to express something about being the only Black person entering all these professional spaces.”"},{type:"text",value:"\u003Cstrong>How the play’s surrealist tone came to be:\u003C/strong> “The main character gets coffee poured on her face in the first scene. For me, that was a big breaking open of the play: ‘This is the kind of world that she’s living in. What else can happen in this world?’ It has what we might call surreal elements, but I don’t always think about it that way because, within this play, everything is real. It’s not a dream.” — \u003Cem>J.A.R.\u003C/em>"},{type:"text",value:"Photo assistant: Serena Nappa. Digital tech: Zachary Smith. Production: Shay Johnson Studio",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"ad",value:{id:89,size:void 0}}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"sectionheader",body:[{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009393908",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009393908",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-beginners-slide-J16T.html",uri:"nyt://image/c131c762-10a7-5513-a30d-cddf1d1547c3",lastModified:"2024-04-04T17:28:09.883Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-04T17:28:09.883Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Kim, photographed at his restaurant, Noksu, in Manhattan on Jan. 15, 2024."},altText:"",credit:"Daniel Terna",summary:"",original:{