:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Lorraine O’Grady’s “Announcement Card 2 (Spike With Sword, Fighting)” (2020)."},altText:"A suit of armor with a spiky helmet and a raised sword.",credit:"© Lorraine O’Grady/Artists Rights Society (ARS), New York, courtesy of Mariane Ibrahim, Chicago, Paris, Mexico City",summary:"",original:{width:2100,height:3150},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:3150,y1:0,x2:2100,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:900},{width:683,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{width:1366,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:2048}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:1181,y1:0,x2:2100,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:1099,y1:0,x2:2100,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:550}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:3150,y1:0,x2:2100,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV/18tmag-halloffame-slide-7EHV-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:2700}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"I thought I was going to be a writer. My family tells me that I made my first poem when I was a year and a half old: “I like mice because they’re nice.” [In my early 30s, after working for five years] as an intelligence analyst, I went to the Iowa Writers’ Workshop for fiction. I hadn’t really been reading fiction, though, so I wasn’t very good at writing it. I spent most of my second year there translating short stories written by my instructor [the Chilean novelist] José Donoso."},{type:"text",value:"Growing up, I had all these exposures to beauty. I’d gone to the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston as a child and seen [Paul] Gauguin’s “Where Do We Come From? What Are We? Where Are We Going?,” a painting that continues to influence me. And my mother was a dress designer. She redid our house every six months. By the time I was 10, I basically had everything that I’m now working with in place, but I didn’t have the language. I didn’t get that language until the early 1970s, when I read [the critic and curator] Lucy Lippard’s “Six Years: The Dematerialization of the Art Object From 1966 to 1972.” [Then] I was ready. The ideas for my visual art already existed within my experience. I just hadn’t known they were art before. "},{type:"text",value:"A few years later, when I was in my early 40s, I had to have a biopsy of my breast. After — thank God, it was negative for cancer — I was thinking about what I could give my doctor as a thank-you present. Reading my copy of the Sunday New York Times, I saw a line in the sports pages about Julius Erving that said, “The doctor is operating again.” I said, “OK, this could be the start of something,” and I made a really good poem for my doctor [out of words clipped from the newspaper]. But when I finished the poem, I said, “This is too good to give to him.” Then I immediately started making newspaper poems for a project called “Cutting Out The New York Times.” I made one every week for 26 weeks. When I finished, I realized that I’d become a visual artist — or revealed that I was a visual artist. — \u003Cem>interview by J.C.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Toni Morrison, ",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"subhed",value:"1931-2019",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"The author of 11 novels, including “Beloved,” “Sula” and “Song of Solomon.”",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"text",value:"By the time Toni Morrison wrote “Beloved” (1987), her best-known novel, she’d worked for nearly two decades as a book editor. Her debut, “The Bluest Eye” (1970), was published when she was 39 and, while not a commercial success, was critically praised. She published three more books between 1973 and 1981 — including “Song of Solomon” — while still at her editing job. "},{type:"text",value:"Prior to going into publishing, Morrison — who had a master’s degree in American literature from Cornell University — spent nearly a decade teaching college English. After her divorce, she worked for a textbook division of Random House before joining Random House proper as its first Black female editor; there, she championed and published Black authors such as Angela Davis, June Jordan, Gayl Jones and Toni Cade Bambara. “I didn’t go to anything. I didn’t join anything,” she once said about the civil rights movement. “But I could make sure there was a published record of those who did march and did put themselves on the line.” All the while, Morrison was waking by dawn to write before heading into the office. She’d later describe those sessions as a form of liberation: “The writing was the real freedom because nobody told me what to do there. That was my world and my imagination. And all my life it’s been that way.” "},{type:"text",value:"For many years, Morrison considered her day job essential to her art. “I thrive on the urgency that doing more than one thing provides,” she once said. But the industry had its difficulties — the overwhelming whiteness, the increasing commercial demands — and she left her position in 1983. Four years later, at age 56, she published “Beloved.” In a preface to the 2004 edition of the book, she looks back on the rush of feelings she experienced following her last day at the job. “I was happy, free in a way I had never been, ever. It was the oddest sensation. Not ecstasy, not satisfaction, not a surfeit of pleasure or accomplishment. It was a purer delight, a rogue anticipation with certainty. Enter ‘Beloved.’”"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Tabboo!, ",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"subhed",value:"65, New York City ",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"The multidisciplinary artist and former drag performer, whose paintings are currently on view at the Dallas Contemporary art space and the MassArt Art Museum in Boston. ",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009395185",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009395185",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-XJ2Z.html",uri:"nyt://image/64d37f28-1141-5495-b532-07cf5fafd65d",lastModified:"2024-04-18T20:32:14.075Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-18T20:32:14.075Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"A 2023 acrylic on canvas by Tabboo! titled “Lavender Garden.”"},altText:"A floral painting with a purple background.",credit:"Courtesy of the artist, Karma and Gordon Robichaux",summary:"",original:{width:8903,height:7540},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:7540,y1:0,x2:8903,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-XJ2Z/18tmag-halloffame-slide-XJ2Z-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:508},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-XJ2Z/18tmag-halloffame-slide-XJ2Z-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:867},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-XJ2Z/18tmag-halloffame-slide-XJ2Z-superJumbo.jpg",name:"super