lways been doing it."},{type:"text",value:"I usually get up at four in the morning. I feed my cat and then start painting. A lot of my paintings are sunrises. And I do sunsets and cityscapes. Or if it rains in a weird way, I’ll do a rain painting. It’s a very spiritual, meditative, private thing. There isn’t a day that goes by that I haven’t done something, and so my work gets better and better and better. And I must say, I’m a master of my craft now. "},{type:"text",value:"Sometimes a collector will ask, “Can we come over to the studio and watch you paint?” I tell them no. I usually do it naked. — \u003Cem>interview by J.C.\u003C/em>"},{type:"ad",value:{id:31,size:void 0}}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Justin Vivian Bond, ",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"subhed",value:"60, New York City and the Hudson Valley, N.Y.",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"The performer and multidisciplinary artist, whose work has been exhibited at Participant Inc. and the New Museum in New York City, and will be on view at Bill Arning Exhibitions in Kinderhook, N.Y., in May.",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009395188",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009395188",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9.html",uri:"nyt://image/51828f64-f4f7-5af8-88a1-5a7347fe72ea",lastModified:"2024-04-17T18:44:04.826Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T18:44:04.826Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Justin Vivian Bond’s watercolor “Witch Eyes, by Viv, to Protect You From Evil Chodes: Lois” (2024)."},altText:"A watercolor of an eye.",credit:"Courtesy of the artist",summary:"",original:{width:2948,height:2917},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:2917,y1:0,x2:2948,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:594},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1013},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:2026}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:2288,y1:629,x2:2948,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:2230,y1:687,x2:2948,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:550}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:2917,y1:0,x2:2948,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9/18tmag-halloffame-slide-5ND9-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:1781}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"text",value:"When I was in high school, I was interested in visual art as well as music and acting, but I decided to major in theater in college because I thought it was a career that could get me out of Maryland and allow me to move to New York. I became a performer, and I’ve been doing cabaret for many years. In 2008, when I broke up my cabaret act Kiki and Herb, my rent was so cheap that I didn’t have to work as much. I started painting again, and it flows very naturally for me."},{type:"text",value:"My watercolors are primarily portraits of people I know. I’ll ask them to pose for a photograph and then paint from that. I also make pseudo fan art, like my “Witch Eyes” series, which is based on iconic photographs of celebrities’ eyes. The wonderful thing about painting is that you have total control over it, if you’re lucky. Onstage, there’re so many variables. And with painting, you don’t have to be there [when people see your work]. I love being in front of an audience, but I don’t really love being among people. The pleasure for me is singing but, when the show’s over, I have to talk to a lot of people. I like all of them, but there’re too many, so it can be a little overwhelming. You don’t ever get to connect on a deeper level. The most satisfying times in my life have been when my shows have been installed and it’s the night before the opening. All of it’s exactly how I want it — the room, the lighting — and I just sit there and look and have this sense of utter satisfaction. — \u003Cem>interview by J.C.\u003C/em>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Wallace Stevens, ",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"subhed",value:"1879-1955",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"The poet, whose best known works include “The Emperor of Ice-Cream,” “The Snow Man” and “Anecdote of the Jar.”",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"text",value:"Wallace Stevens never quit his day job. Though he had literary ambitions as a young man, serving as the editor of the Harvard Advocate as an undergraduate, he earned his degree from New York Law School and in 1916 joined the Hartford Accident and Indemnity Company, where he remained, specializing in surety and fidelity claims, until his death, in 1955. Yet he was writing all the time: on his daily walk to work, at home in the evenings and sometimes in the office."},{type:"text",value:"It wasn’t until 1914, when Stevens was 34, that his first post-college poems appeared in literary journals. He went on to publish seven volumes of poetry over the course of his lifetime. The first, “Harmonium,” released in 1923, sold fewer than 100 copies; the last, 1954’s “The Collected Poems of Wallace Stevens,” won the Pulitzer Prize. "},{type:"text",value:"The themes of Stevens’s work — the affirming power of art and beauty, the sublime contained within the mundane — suggest one reason why he stuck with insurance law even as his artistic acclaim grew. His steady paycheck would have allowed writing to remain a purely creative act. In his essay “Surety and Fidelity Claims,” Stevens says of his insurance work, “You sign a lot of drafts. You see surprisingly few people. ... You don’t even see the country; you see law offices and hotel rooms.” Poetry, on the other hand — as he characterizes it in 1923’s “Of Modern Poetry” — “must be the finding of a satisfaction.” It was his livelihood, in the most artistic sense of the word."}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Theaster Gates, ",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"subhed",value:"50, Chicago",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"The University of Chicago professor and multidisciplinary artist, whose solo shows at the Gagosian gallery in Le Bourget, France, and the Mori Art Museum in Tokyo open this month.",className:"g-detailblock"},{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009395189",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009395189",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-halloffame-slide-28KT.html",uri:"nyt://image/146223a1-c200-5359-a86f-700d944b4788",lastModified:"2024-04-23T21:17:16.089Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-23T21:17:16.089Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Theaster Gates’s sculptural work “Sweet Sanctuary, Your Embrace” (2023)."},altText:"A sculpture resembling a piano covered with white metal.",credit:"© Theaster Gates. Photo: © On White Wall for White Cube",summary:"",original:{width:10404,height:13873},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:13873,y1:0,x2:10404,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/image