’ve come in prepared. Filming the first season of “Industry” in 2019 was the first time I’d been on a job longer than five days, the first time I’d worked out of the country, the first everything, and I was so nervous. Go toward things that scare you. \u003Cstrong>— Myha’la, 28, actor\u003C/strong> "}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Make Yourself Start",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"Deciding what’s a good idea is an ongoing battle. But you can only think about something for so long before you just have to try it. Someone once told me that when he makes a painting he likes, he’ll make another one with the same idea to see if it holds up and then another, which I thought was pretty good advice. Sometimes I force myself to go to my studio and start painting [Gordon initially set out to be a visual artist and started focusing more on her art practice about 25 years ago], even if I don’t have an idea. I like conceptual thinking, but I also like the physicality of painting. Usually that leads me to something and, even if it doesn’t — what am I going to do, sit around and watch movies all day? \u003Cstrong>— Kim Gordon, 70, musician and visual artist\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Put Yourself in Your Body — and Your Past",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:" Sometimes painting can feel like this dream I have where I’m in the back of a moving car and I’m reaching over to the front seat to try to get control. That’s a nervous system in panic. There’s a grounding exercise I like to do where I jump and really feel my feet smack the floor — trying to get yourself back into your body’s part of the trick. And then I go, “Well, who’s dreaming?” If you can get there, you’re lucid in the dream, and that’s a good place to be. Still, feelings will come up that you don’t want. When I was working on this satyr painting, suddenly the satyr was my old friend Chris, who betrayed me when I was 18 to a group of guys who beat me up. I thought, “Why am I painting Chris? I don’t want to paint Chris.” I was in flow for a while but, when I hit this painting, I experienced self-doubt and thought, “People are going to think these paintings are awful.” Then I went on Instagram and liked one of his pictures. It felt like a weird, brave task. And he wrote to me and asked if he could call me, 26 years after ghosting me, and he apologized for 20 minutes. I cried and I think he probably cried, and I felt it all melt away. And then I went back to the painting. \u003Cstrong>— TM Davy, 43, artist\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009398225",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009398225",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y.html",uri:"nyt://image/3a6c92c5-76ef-59ee-9a3d-faf16d6c6449",lastModified:"2024-04-17T18:18:17.676Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T18:18:17.676Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Kim Gordon in 1990."},altText:"Kim Gordon, wearing a floral jumpsuit, poses in front of a red background and extends her left hand.",credit:"Laura Levine/Corbis via Getty Images",summary:"",original:{width:2071,height:3000},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:2944,y1:52,x2:1974,x1:68},bleed:{percentTop:.2420470267534256,percentRight:1.5215109586715698,percentLeft:2.990556240081787,percentBottom:1.7289073467254639},renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y-articleLarge-v2.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:910},{width:675,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y-jumbo-v2.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:1024},{width:1350,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y-superJumbo-v2.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:2048}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:1124,y1:52,x2:1974,x1:68},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y-videoSixteenByNine600-v2.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:1049,y1:52,x2:1974,x1:68},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y-facebookJumbo-v2.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:549}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:2944,y1:52,x2:1974,x1:68},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y/18tmag-advice-slide-NC0Y-mobileMasterAt3x-v2.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:2731}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"300",marginInline:false}},{type:"subhed",value:"Psych Yourself Out",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"If things are too hard, something’s wrong, but you also have to embrace the awkward feelings. See if you can fool yourself — I used to get self-conscious about drawing when I was a teenager in an art class with a model, and the teacher said, “Don’t think of it as drawing. Think of it as designing the page.” That really loosened things up for me. It’s amazing what you can do if you pretend. \u003Cstrong>— Kim Gordon\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Seek Help",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"When people say they’re self-taught, it means they asked somebody else how they did it. When I began in folk music, I went to the clubs and I begged and borrowed and asked. [More recently, having taken up painting acrylics a little over a decade ago,] I was painting [Anthony] Fauci and couldn’t figure out how to do his glasses. I called an artist friend and she had all these tricks — “Don’t try to copy the photograph,” she told me, “just use dabs of paint here and there to give the impression of glass.” It didn’t take more than 45 minutes to learn how to put glasses on Fauci. Without her, I would’ve struggled for weeks trying to get it right. \u003Cstrong>— Joan Baez, 83, singer-songwriter, activist, painter and author\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Don’t Sweat the End — and Work on More Than One Thing at Once",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"Remember that the maker almost never knows exactly what they’re making in advance. The great works often appear when we’re aiming toward something completely different. Start as soon as you see a way in. I [also] find it helpful to work on multiple things at the same time. Not in the same moment but during the same general time period. The beauty is that different projects are at different stages, so you can avoid getting burned out on any one [thing]. We can step away, work on something else and come back with new eyes, as if we’re seeing it for the first time. Tunnel vision’s easy to fall into when working on a single project for a long period. We can end up getting lost in details nobody else will ever notice, while losing touch with the grand gesture of the work. \u003Cstrong>— Rick Rubin, 61, music producer and author of “The Creative Act: A Way of Being”\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009398226",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009398226",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC.html",uri:"nyt://image/9f78e157-620f-5606-bd3c-4c8db7758470",lastModified:"2024-04-08T15:19:10.373Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-08T15:19:10.373Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text:"Murray Hill in 1996."},altText:"",credit:"Catherine McGann/Getty Images",summary:"",original:{width:3000,height:1835},imageType:"photo",crops:[{name:"MASTER",box:{y2:1835,y1:0,x2:3000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC-articleLarge.jpg",name:"articleLarge",height:367},{width:1024,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC-jumbo.jpg",name:"jumbo",height:626},{width:2048,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC-superJumbo.jpg",name:"superJumbo",height:1253}]},{name:"SIXTEEN_BY_NINE",box:{y2:1763,y1:74,x2:3000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:600,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC-videoSixteenByNine600.jpg",name:"videoSixteenByNine600",height:338}]},{name:"FACEBOOK",box:{y2:1703,y1:132,x2:3000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1050,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC-facebookJumbo.jpg",name:"facebookJumbo",height:550}]},{name:"MOBILE_MASTER",box:{y2:1835,y1:0,x2:3000,x1:0},bleed:null,renditions:[{width:1800,url:"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2024/04/18/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC/18tmag-advice-slide-06JC-mobileMasterAt3x.jpg",name:"mobileMasterAt3x",height:1101}]}],mediaComponent:"ImageLoader"},maxWidth:"body",marginInline:false}},{type:"subhed",value:"Treat Procrastination as Productivity",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"There were certain things I couldn’t do during the [SAG-AFTRA] strike, but I did get a book deal. It’s called “Showbiz! My Unexpected Life as a Middle-Aged Man,” and I’ve got to get that done — by June 1st! I’m used to being onstage. When I’m sitting at my desk in my studio apartment, I procrastinate quite a bit, and I’m always asking myself, “Is this part of the creative process for me, or am I just making my life harder?” But I also procrastinate in productive ways. I go for a walk — in rehab, they taught us, “Move a muscle, change a thought.” Then I come back and put on jazz music. Doing that removes the blocks, probably because jazz is so much about improvisation and I’m at my core an improviser. Another thing I’ll do to light the match is turn to others’ work. I’ll watch Dean Martin videos or a documentary or old game shows. For this memoir, I’ve been reading memoirs by other people — Gary Gulman, Viola Davis, Maria Bamford, Leslie Jones, Aparna Nancherla — and not only does that awaken my creative senses, it triggers memories. \u003Cstrong>— Murray Hill, 52, comedian, actor and writer\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"Be Comfortable With Discomfort",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"There was a time when [my] body was always ready, and when I had so many axes to grind and windmills to chase [that] something would come out. Now I can’t just depend on my body being there — that I’m going to bust a move and seduce — so I have to be a little more strategic: “What’s the idea? Does it serve anyone other than you?” I’m trying to reaffirm for myself that what I have left in me to say is worth saying. Doubt is always with us, and it burns like fire. But if I refuse to give up the mantle of being a creative artist, I’ve got to do something. [You might say] “Well, why don’t you just love a child? Why don’t you go work at a soup kitchen down the street?” Because I’m a self-involved son of a bitch. Procrastination says, “I don’t dare,” but can you live with yourself if you don’t? So how do you start? Terror. Guilt. Fear. All negatives to this generation of young people who don’t ever want to be uncomfortable, but the generation that formed me and my own generation had that feeling that you’re being pushed against and you’ve got to push back, because you’re not like them. As Martha Graham said to Agnes de Mille, “There is only a queer divine dissatisfaction, a blessed unrest that keeps us marching and makes us more alive than the others.” I’ve got to believe that about myself, and the evidence is what I dare to do. \u003Cstrong>— Bill T. Jones, 72, choreographer, director and dancer\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"subhed",value:"If Your Work Goes Up in Flames, Don’t Fetishize the Ashes",className:"g-heading2block g-align-left"},{type:"text",value:"One thing that eases the prospect of getting started is remembering that not everything you make needs to be for consumption or even to count as art. I recently spent nine months quietly making these works — mineral paint on cement slabs — and ended up throwing them all away because I decided they were too conventional. You’re not married to your old self, either. In 2013, there was an electrical fire at the studio I’d just moved into, and the building burned to the ground. I lost cartons of negatives and proof sheets that were over six feet tall, as well as photographs — stuff I’d made five, seven, 10, 15 years prior. Of course, it was traumatic and terrifying, but it was also freeing. Eventually I realized it was an opportunity for me to draw a line and stop making a certain kind of work. As artists, we think, “I got known for this type of thing,” or, “This is what everybody seems to like of mine.” A part of me felt, “I have to rebuild this person,” and then I thought, “Well, I don’t,” and I started something else. It was actually one of the most fruitful periods of my creative life. \u003Cstrong>— Anthony Pearson, 55, painter, sculptor and photographer\u003C/strong>"}]},{type:"section",body:[{type:"image",value:{media:{assetType:"scoopImage",assetSlug:"100000009398224",breakpointName:void 0,assetErrors:[],__typename:"Image",sourceId:"100000009398224",url:"/imagepages/2024/04/04/t-magazine/18tmag-advice-slide-CMMT.html",uri:"nyt://image/2ccff783-f51e-59a3-963d-e6ab4bbc63ff",lastModified:"2024-04-17T18:18:47.951Z",lastMajorModification:"2024-04-17T18:18:47.951Z",headline:{default:""},bylines:[],type:"image",caption:{text: